description:
File: lichen/subsys/lichen/oscore/oscore.c
Lines: 659-685

The oscore_ctx_free function wipes cryptographic material but skips peer_eui64:

```c
/* Secure wipe of key material (crypto_wipe cannot be optimized away) */
crypto_wipe(ctx->master_secret, sizeof(ctx->master_secret));
crypto_wipe(ctx->master_salt, sizeof(ctx->master_salt));
crypto_wipe(ctx->sender_key, sizeof(ctx->sender_key));
crypto_wipe(ctx->recipient_key, sizeof(ctx->recipient_key));
crypto_wipe(ctx->common_iv, sizeof(ctx->common_iv));
crypto_wipe(ctx->id_context, sizeof(ctx->id_context)); /* python-ano.74 */
ctx->has_peer_eui64 = false;  // Flag set to false, but peer_eui64 not wiped
ctx->active = false;
```

While peer_eui64 is not cryptographic key material, it is PII (identifies a specific device). Best practice is to wipe all sensitive data on free.

Also missing wipes:
- sender_id (identifies this node)
- recipient_id (identifies peer)

Fix:
```c
crypto_wipe(ctx->peer_eui64, sizeof(ctx->peer_eui64));
crypto_wipe(ctx->sender_id, sizeof(ctx->sender_id));
crypto_wipe(ctx->recipient_id, sizeof(ctx->recipient_id));
```

Or just wipe the entire context:
```c
crypto_wipe(ctx, sizeof(*ctx));
```

Severity: Low - peer_eui64 is not cryptographic secret, but should still be wiped for defense in depth.
